To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the `File` and `Blob` APIs. Here's an example of how you could do this:
```
// Create a new Blob object with the text content
const blob = new Blob([text], {type: 'text/plain'});

// Create a new File object with the blob and a filename
const file = new File([blob], 'example.txt', {type: 'text/plain'});

// Save the file to the user's local storage
file.saveToStorage();
```
This code creates a new `Blob` object with the text content, then creates a new `File` object with the blob and a filename. Finally, it saves the file to the user's local storage using the `saveToStorage()` method.

Keep in mind that this code will only work if the user has granted permission for your web app to access their local storage. You can check whether the user has granted permission by calling the `navigator.storage.requestPermission()` method and checking the result. If the user has not granted permission, you can prompt them to do so using a popup or other UI element.
